---
/**
 * /chain-builder/ (S22): the interactive chain builder. Pick verified THINGs,
 * wire type-checked ports, and watch the planner evaluate the whole system —
 * refusals propagating, materials cascading, every number keeping its citation.
 *
 * The catalog index handed to the island is SLIM (slug + title + taxonomy +
 * branches===null configs); the full compiled artifact and generated fns for a
 * THING load lazily in the island on node-add, so the full catalog's artifacts
 * (~1 MB) never sit in the eager payload. The legality table below is built with the same
 * connectionLegal() the runtime planner uses — real engine verdicts as content.
 */
import { getCollection, getEntry } from "astro:content";
import ChainBuilder from "../components/ChainBuilder";
import { portOf } from "../engines/chain-eval";
import { connectionLegal } from "../engines/units";
import { CATEGORIES, spineOrdered } from "../lib/catalog";
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { withBase } from "../lib/url";

const compiled = await getCollection("compiled");
const things = await getCollection("things");
const taxonomyBy = new Map(
  things.map((t) => [t.data.id, { category: t.data.category, topic: t.data.topic ?? null }]),
);

// buildable catalog: every THING/configuration with branches===null (multi-branch
// four-bar excluded in v1; solve1d configs INCLUDED — the browser runs Brent).
const placeables = compiled
  .map((c) => {
    const tax = taxonomyBy.get(c.data.thing);
    const configs = c.data.configurations
      .filter((cfg) => cfg.branches === null)
      .map((cfg) => ({ id: cfg.id, label: cfg.label }));
    return {
      id: c.data.thing,
      slug: c.data.thing,
      title: c.data.title,
      category: tax?.category ?? "",
      topic: tax?.topic ?? undefined,
      configs,
    };
  })
  .filter((t) => t.configs.length > 0);

const catalog = spineOrdered(placeables).map((t) => ({
  slug: t.slug,
  title: t.title,
  category: t.category,
  topic: t.topic ?? null,
  configs: t.configs,
}));
const categories = CATEGORIES.map((c) => ({ slug: c.slug, name: c.name }));
const materials = (await getCollection("materials")).map((m) => m.data);

// --- curated example chains (S25). Each `frag` is a FROZEN v1 URL fragment
// generated against the merged S23 encoder (never hand-composed) and verified to
// decode with zero drops and reproduce its hand-checked goldens — the proof lives
// in site/e2e/chain-examples.spec.ts. Editing a fragment by hand is forbidden;
// regenerate it from a ChainStore through encodeChain(). ---
const EX_HEADLINE =
  "#";
const EX_BELT =
  "#";
const EX_INDETERMINATE =
  "#";
const chainBuilderPath = withBase("chain-builder/");

// static legality table — real connectionLegal() verdicts over buildable THINGs
const gear = (await getEntry("compiled", "planetary-gearset"))!.data;
const shaft = (await getEntry("compiled", "torsion-shaft"))!.data;
const flywheel = (await getEntry("compiled", "flywheel-disk"))!.data;
const column = (await getEntry("compiled", "euler-column"))!.data;
const motor = (await getEntry("compiled", "dc-motor"))!.data;
// same Port constructor the runtime planner uses (invariant 4, one definition)
const checks = [
  { from: "motor T — torque", to: "planetary T_s — torque", res: connectionLegal(portOf(motor, "T"), portOf(gear, "T_s")) },
  { from: "planetary T_out — torque", to: "shaft T — torque", res: connectionLegal(portOf(gear, "T_out"), portOf(shaft, "T")) },
  { from: "planetary ω_c — angular velocity", to: "flywheel ω — angular velocity", res: connectionLegal(portOf(gear, "omega_c"), portOf(flywheel, "omega")) },
  { from: "planetary ω_c — angular velocity", to: "shaft T — torque", res: connectionLegal(portOf(gear, "omega_c"), portOf(shaft, "T")) },
  { from: "planetary N_r — tooth count", to: "column K — end-fixity ratio", res: connectionLegal(portOf(gear, "N_r"), portOf(column, "K")) },
];
---

<Base
  title="Chain builder"
  description="Wire verified THINGs into a system: pick components, connect type-checked ports, and watch the planner evaluate the whole chain with every number keeping its citation."
>
  <h1>Chain builder</h1>
  <p>
    Every machine is THINGs wired together. Pick components from the catalog, connect one THING's
    output port to another's input, and the planner evaluates the whole chain in dependency order —
    stress, twist, stored energy, and safety factors propagating from node to node. A connection is
    legal only when the SI dimension <strong>and</strong> the quantity kind both match (invariant 2),
    so a torque can never be mistaken for an energy, nor an angle for a ratio. Swap a downstream
    material and watch the numbers move; drive a node past its validity envelope and watch the
    refusal propagate — a refused value is <em>withheld</em>, never forwarded as a plausible wrong
    number (invariant 5).
  </p>
  <p class="citation">
    This is the v1 builder: forward chains only, up to six nodes, single-branch configurations. For a
    fixed worked example see the <a href={withBase("chain-demo/")}>chaining demo</a> (a planetary
    reduction driving a torsion shaft, power conserved through the wiring).
  </p>

  <section class="cb-examples" aria-labelledby="examples-heading" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <h2 id="examples-heading">Start from an example</h2>
    <p>
      Wiring a legal chain from scratch takes some knowing-what-connects-to-what. These three are
      built and verified — open one to load it into the builder below, then turn its knobs and watch
      the consequences travel. Every number keeps the citation trail (<em>Where this comes from</em>)
      and the assumptions panel you see under any chain.
    </p>
    <ul class="cb-example-grid">
      <li class="cb-example">
        <h3>Spin-up time vs. shaft stress</h3>
        <p>
          The headline. A <strong>permanent-magnet DC motor</strong>, running at its peak-power
          point (100 N·m at 150 rad/s — <strong>15 kW</strong>), drives a ring-fixed
          <strong>planetary reduction</strong> with its torque <em>and</em> shaft speed wired
          across; the 3.5:1 ratio turns the motor's 100 N·m into
          <strong>T_out = 350 N·m</strong> delivered to the load. That one torque does two jobs at
          once. Wired into a <strong>driveshaft</strong> (with the carrier speed wired across too,
          so the shaft carries the full <strong>15 kW</strong> the motor put in — power survives
          the wiring), it winds the shaft to <strong>τ = 27.9 MPa</strong>. Wired into a steel
          <strong>flywheel</strong>, the same torque spins it up from rest to 300 rad/s in
          <strong>t_spin = 0.13 s</strong>. Now crank the gear ratio up (drop the sun teeth
          <code>N_s</code>): the flywheel spins up faster <em>and</em> the shaft winds tighter.
          Storing energy quickly costs shaft stress — that is the trade.
        </p>
        <a class="cb-example-link" data-chain-example href={`${chainBuilderPath}${EX_HEADLINE}`}>
          Open this chain <span aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        </a>
      </li>
      <li class="cb-example">
        <h3>A belt drive sizing a shaft</h3>
        <p>
          A flat <strong>belt on the verge of slip</strong> (400 N tight side, 180° wrap, μ = 0.3)
          transmits <strong>P = 3.15 kW</strong>. Feed that power into a <strong>shaft</strong> in its
          <em>power-in</em> configuration: the shaft first backs out the torque it must carry,
          <strong>T = P/ω = 31.5 N·m</strong> at 100 rad/s, then the shear that torque produces,
          <strong>τ = 2.50 MPa</strong>. Two unrelated physics — capstan friction and the torsion
          formula — chained by the one quantity both speak, <strong>power</strong>.
        </p>
        <a class="cb-example-link" data-chain-example href={`${chainBuilderPath}${EX_BELT}`}>
          Open this chain <span aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        </a>
      </li>
      <li class="cb-example">
        <h3>A gearbox into a doubly-clamped shaft</h3>
        <p>
          The same planetary delivers <strong>350 N·m</strong> — now into a shaft built into a wall at
          <em>both</em> ends, with the torque applied off-centre. That shaft is
          <strong>statically indeterminate</strong>: equilibrium alone cannot split the torque between
          the two walls. The build solves the coupled 2×2 compatibility system exactly, so the chain
          shows <strong>T_A = 210 N·m</strong> on the shorter segment and <strong>T_B = 140 N·m</strong>
          on the longer — a Phase-3 indeterminate solve fed by a chain. Swap the shaft's material and
          the reactions do not move (the GJ cancels); only the twist does.
        </p>
        <a class="cb-example-link" data-chain-example href={`${chainBuilderPath}${EX_INDETERMINATE}`}>
          Open this chain <span aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        </a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <div data-pagefind-ignore>
    <ChainBuilder client:load catalog={catalog} categories={categories} materials={materials} />
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    // Example-chain links load a frozen chain into the builder. The builder decodes
    // the URL fragment ONCE at mount (S23) and has no hashchange listener, so when a
    // visitor clicks an example while ALREADY on this page a bare same-page hash
    // change would update the URL without rebuilding the chain. Force a reload so the
    // island remounts and re-decodes. Arriving from another page loads fresh anyway,
    // so this only intercepts the same-page case (progressive enhancement — the link
    // still works without JS from elsewhere in the site).
    document.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
      // let the browser handle modified / non-primary clicks (open-in-new-tab,
      // download, etc.) — only intercept a plain left-click.
      if (e.button !== 0 || e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey || e.shiftKey || e.altKey) return;
      const a = e.target.closest && e.target.closest("a[data-chain-example]");
      if (!a || !a.hash) return;
      if (location.pathname === new URL(a.href, location.href).pathname) {
        e.preventDefault();
        // set the fragment via replaceState (no history spam, matching the
        // builder's URL-sync convention), then reload so the island re-decodes it.
        history.replaceState(history.state, "", a.href);
        location.reload();
      }
    });
  </script>

  <h2>Connections are type-checked</h2>
  <p>
    A binding is legal iff the SI dimension 7-vector <strong>and</strong> the quantity kind both
    match. Dimensions alone are not enough: an angle and a Poisson ratio are both dimensionless, and
    torque shares dimensions with energy. The verdicts below come from the same
    <code>connectionLegal()</code> the builder runs when you press <em>Connect</em>:
  </p>
  <div class="table-scroll">
    <table class="material-props">
      <thead>
        <tr><th scope="col">From port</th><th scope="col">To port</th><th scope="col">Engine verdict</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {
          checks.map((c) => (
            <tr>
              <td>{c.from}</td>
              <td>{c.to}</td>
              <td>
                {c.res.ok ? (
                  <span class="chain-ok">legal</span>
                ) : (
                  <span class="chain-no">rejected — {c.res.reason}</span>
                )}
              </td>
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p class="citation">
    The planner also rejects any binding that would close a feedback loop — cyclic solving is out of
    scope in v1 (relations are stored undirected, so a cyclic solver can be added later without
    rewriting THINGs). Everything here is computed in the browser from build-time-verified functions;
    the site remains a pure static site.
  </p>
</Base>
